d)\\n\\nFrances: timestamped selfie on her phone showing she was at the lake at 7:55pm; got back inside the house at 8:20 (unusually slow because of the snow). Could be lying about slowness and got back sooner to kill Victor, then made a show of returning from walk at 8:20 to be seen by Melissa. We tested the route ourselves and confirmed it wasn't possible for Frances to make it back and attack Victor in the necessary time window.\\n\\nMelissa: short black hair (could match hair at crime scene), tall but frail, cane with a yellow tennis ball (responsible for odd mud scuff marks?), not bothered about Victor's death since they haven't been in love for a long time. Can't confirm her alibi but for the claim that she's too frail to have pushed Victor over.\",\"Victim: uncle Victor; died during the night; hard of hearing; never slept late and odd that he wasn't up by 7:30\\nSuspects: Frances, aunt Melissa, cousin Nathan. All 3 found the body together (around 9am), Frances called the police\\n\\nSnowfall ended around 7pm, we arrived at the house after midnight and went to sleep\\n\\nBody: facedown with a large gash in the forehead; deep enough to be fatal & matches shape of hearth; fell directly forward; not wearing hearing aids or glasses (unusual); was likely deliberately pushed with some force by someone standing directly behind him\\nRoom: bloodstained hearth; smashed vases & lamp; scattered books & papers; patches of mud; old room with uneven floor in basement with 2 small windows high in the back wall overlooking garden shrubs; door lock's been broken but Frances claims Nathan did that because Victor wasn't answering their calls\\nLock: Victor lost the key over a year ago, and without it the door can only be locked & unlocked from inside the room\\nWindows: open outwards, both shut & locked from the inside, no screen, only a very small person or child could fit through, 6-7 inches above the ground\\nFireplace: regularly used, probably in use last night\\nDebris: vas